<paragraph id="8BE4BD5F1D132B4A5D99FA75764B54EA" blockId="14.[118,768,1279,1502]" pageId="14" pageNumber="337">
<emphasis id="B92F614D1D132B4A5D99FA7576A754AA" box="[163,443,1414,1438]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="337">Distribution and ecology</emphasis>
. – 
<taxonomicName id="4C5BC6DC1D132B4A5CDBFA7575F954AA" authorityName="Callm. &amp; Buerki. STONE" authorityYear="1978" baseAuthorityName="Merr." box="[481,741,1414,1438]" class="Liliopsida" family="Pandanaceae" genus="Benstonea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="14" pageNumber="337" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pachyphylla">
<emphasis id="B92F614D1D132B4A5CDBFA7575F954AA" box="[481,741,1414,1438]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="337">Benstonea pachyphylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to the lowland rainforests of Borneo (Kalimatan, 
<collectingRegion id="499F73BD1D132B4A5D4CFA3577AB54EA" box="[118,183,1478,1502]" country="Malaysia" name="Sabah" pageId="14" pageNumber="337">Sabah</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F34CFDCF1D132B4A5DD1FA35765054EA" box="[235,332,1478,1502]" name="Malaysia" pageId="14" pageNumber="337">Sarawak</collectingCountry>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C341EED41D132B4A5D99FA1D76AD57F2" pageId="14" pageNumber="337" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BE4BD5F1D132B4A5D99FA1D76AD57F2" blockId="14.[118,771,1518,1734]" pageId="14" pageNumber="337">
<emphasis id="B92F614D1D132B4A5D99FA1D762F5732" box="[163,307,1518,1542]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="337">Observations</emphasis>
. – This species is very characteristic, with its acaulescent habit and syncarp borne in the middle of a large clump of leaves growing directly from the ground (
<figureCitation id="1360A1DA1D132B4A5FA6F9DD75EF5772" box="[668,755,1582,1606]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[118,143,1873,1893]" captionTargetBox="[118,1494,265,1835]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 4. – Infructescences and details of stigmas of species of Benstonea Callm. &amp; Buerki. A. Benstonea affinis (Kurz) Callm. &amp; Buerki; B. Benstonea gibbsiana (Martelli) Callm. &amp; Buerki; C. Benstonea ornata (Solms) Callm. &amp; Buerki; D. Benstonea pachyphylla (Merr.) Callm. &amp; Buerki. [Photos: M. W. Callmander]" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5799762" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5799762/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="337">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
). Its leaves are similar to those of the poorly known 
<taxonomicName id="4C5BC6DC1D132B4A5FBDF9BD75E95752" box="[647,757,1614,1638]" class="Liliopsida" family="Pandanaceae" genus="Benstonea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="14" pageNumber="337" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="celebica">
<emphasis id="B92F614D1D132B4A5FBDF9BD75E95752" box="[647,757,1614,1638]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="337">B.celebica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the latter only known by its leaves and a picture of the fruit (see above). These may represent a single species that occurs in both 
<collectingRegion id="499F73BD1D132B4A5DFDF95D763B57F2" box="[199,295,1710,1734]" country="Indonesia" name="Sulawesi Utara" pageId="14" pageNumber="337">Sulawesi</collectingRegion>
and Borneo.
</paragraph>
